<!--
========================================================================
FILE: ProductList.view.xml — Product Listing with Search, Sort, Filter
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS THIS VIEW?
This view displays a list of products within a selected category. It
includes a toolbar for searching and sorting, and each product is
shown as an ObjectListItem with its name, price, rating, and stock.

[INTERMEDIATE] KEY CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED:
  - Toolbar with SearchField and sort controls
  - List with growing (lazy loading) feature
  - ObjectListItem for structured data display
  - Aggregation binding with OData entity set
  - Formatter functions for price and availability
  - Event handling for search, sort, and navigation

Learn more: docs/06-controls.md, docs/10-filtering-sorting.md
========================================================================
-->

<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.ProductList"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
>
    <!--
    [BEGINNER] PAGE WITH BACK NAVIGATION
    ====================================================
    showNavButton="true"
      Shows a back-arrow (<) button in the page header.
      This is standard for sub-pages (pages you navigate TO,
      not the landing page).

    navButtonPress=".onNavBack"
      [BEGINNER] Fires when the user presses the back button.
      The controller's onNavBack method typically calls:
        window.history.go(-1)  or  router.navTo("home")

    title="{i18n>productsTitle}"
      Page title bound to i18n for translation support.

    [INTERMEDIATE] PAGE vs. SEMANTIC PAGE
    sap.m.Page is simple and works for most cases.
    sap.f.semantic.SemanticPage provides pre-defined positions
    for standard actions (edit, delete, share, etc.) following
    Fiori design guidelines. For production Fiori apps, prefer
    SemanticPage. For learning, sap.m.Page is clearer.
    -->
    <Page
        id="productListPage"
        title="{i18n>productsTitle}"
        showNavButton="true"
        navButtonPress=".onNavBack"
    >
        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <subHeader> AGGREGATION
        ====================================================
        The Page control has a special aggregation called "subHeader"
        that renders a bar BELOW the main header. It's perfect for
        search and filter controls that should stay visible while
        the content scrolls.

        Think of it like a sticky toolbar below the page title.

        [INTERMEDIATE] TOOLBAR vs. BAR
        UI5 has two similar controls for horizontal layouts:
          - sap.m.Bar: Simple left/middle/right layout (3 sections)
          - sap.m.Toolbar: Flexible container that lays items with flexbox
          - sap.m.OverflowToolbar: Toolbar that collapses items into a
            "..." overflow menu on small screens

        [BEST PRACTICE] Use OverflowToolbar instead of Toolbar when
        your toolbar has many items. On mobile, items that don't fit
        automatically move into an overflow popover (the "..." button).
        This ensures usability across screen sizes without custom code.
        -->
        <subHeader>
            <OverflowToolbar>
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] THE <SearchField> CONTROL
                ====================================================
                sap.m.SearchField renders a search input with a search
                icon button. It's the standard way to add search
                functionality in UI5 apps.

                id="searchField"
                  Giving it an ID lets the controller access it to
                  read the current search value:
                    this.byId("searchField").getValue()

                placeholder="{i18n>search}"
                  Ghost text shown when the field is empty.
                  Bound to i18n key: "Search products..."

                search=".onSearch"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] EVENT: liveChange vs. search
                    - liveChange: Fires on EVERY keystroke as the user
                      types. Provides instant/live filtering.
                    - search: Fires only when user presses Enter or
                      clicks the search icon. Better for server-side
                      filtering (avoids too many requests).

                  For client-side filtering with mock data, liveChange
                  gives a better user experience (instant results).
                  For real OData services with large datasets, use
                  the "search" event to avoid hammering the server.

                  [ADVANCED] DEBOUNCING
                  If using liveChange with server-side search, add a
                  debounce delay in the controller (e.g., wait 300ms
                  after the last keystroke before sending the request).
                  UI5 doesn't do this automatically.

                width="auto"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] Setting width to "auto" lets the
                  SearchField take available space in the toolbar.
                  Combined with ToolbarSpacer, this creates a flexible
                  responsive layout.
                -->
                <SearchField
                    id="searchField"
                    placeholder="{i18n>search}"
                    search=".onSearch"
                    width="auto"
                />

                <!--
                [BEGINNER] THE <ToolbarSpacer> CONTROL
                ====================================================
                sap.m.ToolbarSpacer is a utility control that pushes
                subsequent items to the right. It renders as a flex
                spacer (flex-grow: 1) in the toolbar.

                Before ToolbarSpacer:  [Search] [Sort] [Filter]
                After ToolbarSpacer:   [Search]            [Sort] [Filter]

                It's like CSS margin-left: auto on the next element.
                -->
                <ToolbarSpacer />

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] THE <Select> CONTROL — Dropdown for Sorting
                ====================================================
                sap.m.Select renders a dropdown/combobox for single
                value selection. We use it here to let users choose
                how to sort the product list.

                change=".onSortChange"
                  Fires when the user selects a different sort option.
                  The controller reads the selected key and applies a
                  Sorter to the list binding.

                [INTERMEDIATE] Select vs. ComboBox
                  - Select: Dropdown only, user MUST pick from options
                  - ComboBox: Dropdown + free text input with autocomplete
                  - MultiComboBox: ComboBox that allows multiple selections

                Use Select when the options are limited and predefined.
                Use ComboBox when the user might want to type to filter
                or when there are many options.
                -->
                <Select
                    id="sortSelect"
                    change=".onSortChange"
                    tooltip="{i18n>sortBy}"
                >
                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] <core:Item> — Dropdown Option
                    ====================================================
                    Each <core:Item> represents one option in the dropdown.

                    key: A programmatic identifier (not shown to users).
                         Used in the controller to determine which sort
                         to apply.
                    text: The user-visible label.

                    The core: prefix means this control is from the
                    sap.ui.core library, not sap.m. Item is a base
                    control used across many UI5 controls (Select,
                    ComboBox, List, etc.).
                    -->
                    <core:Item key="Name" text="{i18n>sortBy}: Name" />
                    <core:Item key="Price" text="{i18n>sortBy}: Price" />
                    <core:Item key="Rating" text="{i18n>sortBy}: Rating" />
                </Select>

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] BUTTON TO OPEN ViewSettingsDialog
                ====================================================
                This button opens a ViewSettingsDialog for advanced
                filtering and sorting. The dialog is typically defined
                as a Fragment (reusable XML snippet) and loaded in the
                controller.

                icon="sap-icon://sort"
                  Shows only an icon (no text) to save toolbar space.
                  On narrow screens, icon-only buttons are more practical.

                press=".onOpenViewSettings"
                  Opens the ViewSettingsDialog fragment.

                [ADVANCED] ViewSettingsDialog provides a standardized
                Fiori UI for:
                  - Sorting by multiple fields
                  - Filtering by multiple criteria
                  - Grouping list items by a field
                All without you building the UI manually.
                -->
                <Button
                    icon="sap-icon://sort"
                    press=".onOpenViewSettings"
                    tooltip="{i18n>sortBy}"
                />
            </OverflowToolbar>
        </subHeader>

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <List> CONTROL — Displaying Collections
        ====================================================
        sap.m.List is one of the MOST IMPORTANT controls in UI5.
        It renders a scrollable list of items, each based on a template.

        id="productList"
          Used by the controller to access the list and its binding:
            var oList = this.byId("productList");
            var oBinding = oList.getBinding("items");
            oBinding.filter(aFilters);

        [INTERMEDIATE] THE growing AND growingThreshold PROPERTIES
        ====================================================
        growing="true"
          Enables LAZY LOADING (also called "growing" in UI5).
          Instead of loading ALL products at once, the list loads
          a small batch and shows a "More" button (or triggers
          auto-loading on scroll) to load the next batch.

          This is critical for performance with large datasets:
            - 10,000 products? Load 8 at a time, not all 10,000.
            - The OData model automatically adds $top and $skip
              parameters to request only the needed batch.

        growingThreshold="8"
          How many items to load per batch. The first load gets 8
          items, pressing "More" loads 8 more, and so on.

          [BEST PRACTICE] Choose a threshold that fills about 1.5
          screens. This way:
            - The user sees a full screen of items immediately
            - There are a few items below the fold to hint "more content"
            - The "More" button or scroll trigger is just off-screen

        growingScrollToLoad="true"
          [ADVANCED] When true, new items load automatically when
          the user scrolls near the bottom (infinite scroll).
          When false, a "More" button is shown at the bottom.

          Infinite scroll feels more natural but makes it harder
          to reach the page footer. Use with caution.

        noDataText="{i18n>noProducts}"
          [BEGINNER] Text shown when the list has NO items.
          This happens when:
            - The OData service returns an empty collection
            - All items are filtered out by search/filter
            - Data hasn't loaded yet (briefly, before the response)

          [BEST PRACTICE] Always set noDataText to guide the user.
          An empty list with no explanation is confusing UX.

        [BEGINNER] AGGREGATION BINDING ON THE LIST
        ====================================================
        items="{/Products}"
          This binds the "items" aggregation to the /Products
          OData entity set. For each product entity returned by
          the OData service, UI5 creates one ObjectListItem using
          the template defined inside <items>.

          The OData model sends: GET /Products?$top=8
          (Because growing is enabled with threshold 8)

        [ADVANCED] COMPLEX AGGREGATION BINDING SYNTAX
        For more control, use the object syntax:
          items="{
            path: '/Products',
            sorter: { path: 'Name' },
            filters: [{ path: 'CategoryId', operator: 'EQ', value1: 'CAT001' }],
            parameters: {
              expand: 'Category',
              select: 'ProductId,Name,Price,Currency,Stock,Rating'
            }
          }"

          - sorter: Default sort order
          - filters: Default filters applied
          - parameters.expand: Include related entities (OData $expand)
          - parameters.select: Request only specific fields (OData $select)

        [BEST PRACTICE] Use $select to request only the fields you
        need. This reduces payload size and improves performance,
        especially on slow networks.
        -->
        <List
            id="productList"
            items="{/Products}"
            growing="true"
            growingThreshold="8"
            growingScrollToLoad="true"
            noDataText="{i18n>noProducts}"
        >
            <!--
            [BEGINNER] THE <ObjectListItem> — Rich List Item
            ====================================================
            sap.m.ObjectListItem is a specialized list item designed
            for displaying business objects (products, orders, employees).

            It has pre-defined slots for common attributes:
              - title:       Main text (product name)
              - number:      Numeric value (price)
              - numberUnit:  Unit for the number (currency)
              - intro:       Small text above the title (category name)
              - icon:        Image/avatar on the left
              - attributes:  Key-value pairs below the title
              - firstStatus: Status indicator (colored text)
              - secondStatus: Another status indicator
              - markers:     Flag/favorite markers

            This structure follows SAP Fiori design guidelines for
            list items — consistent layout across all SAP apps.

            [INTERMEDIATE] ObjectListItem vs. StandardListItem vs. CustomListItem
              - StandardListItem: Simple — icon, title, description, info
              - ObjectListItem: Rich — title, number, attributes, statuses
              - CustomListItem: Fully custom — you define the entire layout

            ObjectListItem is ideal for product listings because products
            naturally have a name (title), price (number), and attributes
            like rating and availability.

            type="Navigation"
              [BEGINNER] Shows a chevron (>) on the right side,
              indicating this item navigates somewhere when pressed.
              Users learn to associate the chevron with "tap to see more".

            press=".onProductPress"
              [BEGINNER] Fires when the user taps/clicks this item.
              The controller reads the ProductId from the binding
              context and navigates to the productDetail route.

              In the controller:
                onProductPress: function(oEvent) {
                  var oItem = oEvent.getSource();
                  var oCtx = oItem.getBindingContext();
                  var sProductId = oCtx.getProperty("ProductId");
                  this.getRouter().navTo("productDetail", {
                    productId: sProductId
                  });
                }

            title="{Name}"
              Bound to the product's Name property.
              Shows as the main text: "Wireless Mouse", "Laptop Pro 15"

            number="{
                path: 'Price',
                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
            }"
              [INTERMEDIATE] BINDING WITH FORMATTER
              This uses a FORMATTER to transform the raw price value
              before displaying it.

              Breaking it down:
                path: 'Price'  → Read the Price value from the model
                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                  → Pass it through the formatPrice function
                  → The "." means "on the controller instance"
                  → Controller has: formatter: formatter (imported module)
                  → So this resolves to: formatter.formatPrice(priceValue)

              Flow: Model Price (42.5) → formatPrice(42.5) → "$42.50"

              [GOTCHA] The path is RELATIVE (no leading /) because
              we're inside a list binding. Each item has its own
              binding context (e.g., /Products('P001')), and 'Price'
              resolves relative to that context.

            numberUnit="{Currency}"
              The unit displayed next to the number: "USD", "EUR"
              Shows as: "$42.50 USD"

            [BEST PRACTICE] Use the number + numberUnit properties
            together. UI5 handles their layout responsively — on
            narrow screens, the number may wrap below the title.
            -->
            <ObjectListItem
                type="Navigation"
                press=".onProductPress"
                title="{Name}"
                number="{
                    path: 'Price',
                    formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                }"
                numberUnit="{Currency}"
                icon="{ImageUrl}"
            >
                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] THE <attributes> AGGREGATION
                ====================================================
                ObjectListItem's "attributes" aggregation holds
                ObjectAttribute controls that display below the title
                as key-value pairs.

                These are used for supplementary information that
                supports the main content (title + number).

                [BEGINNER] ObjectAttribute
                  title: The label (e.g., "Rating")
                  text:  The value (e.g., "4.7 / 5")

                We show Rating with the formatRating formatter to
                clean up decimal places (4.66667 → "4.7").
                -->
                <attributes>
                    <ObjectAttribute
                        title="{i18n>rating}"
                        text="{
                            path: 'Rating',
                            formatter: '.formatter.formatRating'
                        }"
                    />
                </attributes>

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] THE <firstStatus> AGGREGATION
                ====================================================
                ObjectListItem has two status slots: firstStatus and
                secondStatus. These render as colored ObjectStatus
                controls aligned to the right of the item.

                We use firstStatus to show the product's availability
                (In Stock / Low Stock / Out of Stock) with semantic
                coloring (green / orange / red).

                [BEGINNER] ObjectStatus — Semantic Status Display
                ====================================================
                sap.m.ObjectStatus shows a colored text indicator.

                text="{path: 'Stock', formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailability'}"
                  Converts stock count to readable text:
                    0  → "Out of Stock"
                    3  → "Low Stock"
                    15 → "In Stock"

                state="{path: 'Stock', formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailabilityState'}"
                  Controls the COLOR of the text:
                    0  → ValueState.Error   (red)
                    3  → ValueState.Warning (orange)
                    15 → ValueState.Success (green)

                [BEST PRACTICE] Notice the PAIRED FORMATTERS pattern:
                  - formatAvailability  → provides the TEXT
                  - formatAvailabilityState → provides the COLOR

                Both read from the same model property (Stock) but
                output different types of values. This pattern keeps
                text and color synchronized automatically.

                [ADVANCED] ACCESSIBILITY NOTE
                Screen readers announce the state along with the text:
                  "In Stock, Success" or "Out of Stock, Error"
                This gives visually impaired users the same semantic
                information that sighted users get from color.
                -->
                <firstStatus>
                    <ObjectStatus
                        text="{
                            path: 'Stock',
                            formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailability'
                        }"
                        state="{
                            path: 'Stock',
                            formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailabilityState'
                        }"
                    />
                </firstStatus>
            </ObjectListItem>
        </List>

    </Page>

</mvc:View>
